name: N-acetyl-l-tyrosine
Reason:
To predict the melting point of N-acetyl-l-tyrosine, we need to consider the various functional groups and their influence on melting point as compared to a reference compound. As a reference, we can use the base structure benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The functional groups that we need to consider are: (1) a carboxylic acid group, (2) an amide group from N-acetylation, (3) a hydroxyl group, and (4) a phenyl ring from the tyrosine structure.
(1) A carboxylic acid group generally contributes to an increased melting point due to hydrogen bonding potential; this can add around +80°C to the melting point.
(2) An amide group also engages in hydrogen bonding, but less so than a carboxylic acid due to its resonance stabilization of the lone pair on the nitrogen; for a simple amide, this can contribute around +40°C.
(3) A hydroxyl group will further increase the melting point due to hydrogen bonding, contributing approximately +40°C.
(4) The phenyl ring contributes significantly to van der Waals interactions due to its large surface area, which can add around +100°C. Other minor steric factors and intramolecular interactions could slightly adjust the temperature but are not considered quantifiable for this rough estimation.
Combining these effects, the predicted melting point for N-acetyl-l-tyrosine is obtained by adding the contributions of the functional groups to the reference benzene melting point.
